{
  "text": "In our study we found that the application of an asset-based approach was relevant and had potential for PWA and their family members, across countries and cultures. Exploring the lived experience of aphasia, using this approach, has proven feasible. Our research supports Brown et al. (2012) , in calling for a transformation of rehabilitation for PWA, where the central focus is on how people can remain connected to the things that keep them well, rather than a focus on needs or deficits. While the concept of living successfully with aphasia is not a new one (Brown et al., 2012; [CITATION_1] , an asset-based approach provides and strong theoretical basis and a practical framework (e.g. Hopkins and Ripon, 2015; Ripon and South, 2017) to enable this transformation.",
